Metronidazole, marketed under the brand name Flagyl, is an antiparasitic and antibacterial medication that was first introduced in the late 1960s. It belongs to a class of drugs called nitroimidazoles and works by disrupting DNA replication in parasites and bacteria, ultimately leading to their death. Over the years, it has been used to treat a wide range of conditions such as giardiasis, amoebiasis, trichomoniasis, and bacterial vaginosis. Its effectiveness against these conditions led to its approval by the FDA in 1974 for the treatment of trichomoniasis and bacterial vaginosis. Since then, its indications have been expanded to include the treatment of other infections such as pelvic inflammatory disease, abscesses, and sexually transmitted infections like chlamydia and gonorrhea. Today, it remains one of the most commonly prescribed antibiotics worldwide.
